      <strong>🔑 Key Note:</strong> Peak hour pricing only applies to consumers with <strong>sanctioned load of 5kW or above</strong>. If your connection is below 5kW, peak hours do not affect your per-unit rate — but shifting usage still reduces your total consumption and keeps you in lower tariff slabs.
    </div>

    <h2>Why Does KPK Have Earlier Peak Hours?</h2>
    <p>PESCO and TESCO (Khyber Pakhtunkhwa) have winter peak hours from 5:00 PM to 9:00 PM — one hour earlier than Punjab and Sindh. This reflects the geographic reality: winter days end earlier in KPK due to its higher latitude and mountain terrain. Demand for lighting and heating spikes earlier in the evening across Peshawar, Swat, Abbottabad, and other KPK cities.</p>

    <h2>The 5 Appliances That Spike Your Bill During Peak Hours</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Air Conditioner (1.5 ton):</strong> Consumes 1.5 to 2.0 kWh/hour. Running during peak adds Rs 70–100/hour at unprotected rates plus surcharges.</li>
      <li><strong>Electric Geyser:</strong> Consumes 2.0 to 3.0 kWh/hour. Heat water in the afternoon — stored hot water in an insulated tank stays warm for hours.</li>
      <li><strong>Washing Machine + Dryer:</strong> 1.5 to 2.5 kWh per cycle. Run after 10:30 PM or before noon.</li>
      <li><strong>Electric Iron:</strong> 1.0 to 2.0 kWh per hour. Iron clothes in the morning on weekends.</li>
      <li><strong>Electric Oven / Microwave:</strong> 1.0 to 2.5 kWh per use. Cook early or use gas cooking during peak hours.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Simple Rule to Remember</h2>
